  "enhanced_information": "In cases of suspected congenital adrenal hyperplasia (CAH) in a pregnant female, the primary goal is to prevent fetal virilization due to excess androgen exposure. Dexamethasone is the drug of choice as it effectively reduces androgen production from the adrenal glands. While hydrocortisone is used for adrenal insufficiency, it is not the first-line treatment for preventing virilization in this context. Betamethasone is primarily indicated for fetal lung maturity and is not recommended for CAH management. Prednisolone is less effective than dexamethasone for this condition. Therefore, the consensus supports that dexamethasone is the preferred treatment for managing suspected CAH in pregnancy."
}
